Author::::MadChinchillaLady
DateTime::::2016-02-29T01:22:56Z
What there would be, is, as just one example, a bunch of struggling kids like I was, who are embarrassed and scared by their need to touch things symmetrically, their counting rituals, distressed by their sometimes terrifying thoughts that flash up endless horrific images, who lose so much time performing their rituals, mental and physical, until things feel 'right' and who have absolutely no idea there's a specific name for what they have and other people like them. I still had a mental illness back then, I just didn't know that's what it was. It didn't resolve by itself, it got worse, over a period of eight years. Learning what it was enabled me to gain some way of dealing with it. It being treated as 'stress' would not have done that, because that's not what it is. Nor does a biomedical model mean mediation is always required (I don't take medication currently. For some people it is helpful), or that people cannot recover or manage their conditions without them. For me, no the medication wasn't going to just resolve everything as a treatment, but that's not what people are expecting it to do. The idea was it would reduce my anxiety and make it easier to handle day to day life and the exposure therapy, because (as one book on OCD very accurately put it), asking someone with OCD to do exposure therapy can feel to them like asking them to stand in front of an oncoming train and not react to it. It's not really that different to my painkillers for nerve damage, it won't fix it, but it dampens down the amount of pain.



