Author::::Kerry26
DateTime::::2016-02-28T22:14:08Z
After reading some comments to this article, something I just don’t understand is why scientists fail to grasp that changes in mind-states (such as worry, rumination, etc.) that happen as a result of various outside factors (losing a job, losing a loved one, etc.) CAUSE structural changes in the brain. When outside problems are resolved with time, the brain gets back to normal again (there are SO MANY research studies from the fields of ‘neuroplasticity’ and ‘epigenetics’ as well as other studies supporting this). But if a person is given a label and told that they have a “mental illness” - having that label itself can be devastating to an individual over time, leading to thoughts such as “why me?” “I am doomed for life”, etc., and these thoughts can lead to more worries and depression over time and also result in adverse structural changes in the brain. If anyone has data that show mental illnesses are brain diseases, I would be very interested to see - I would like to see specific studies, not mere correlations. Someone came up with this brain “myth” one day, and everyone now just blindly believes it! This ‘belief’ also gets passed on from generation to generation! In other organs in the body (organs like the liver, spleen, etc.) biological abnormalities are extremely rare. Because scientists do not understand the mind, they simply explain every psychological problem as a “biological abnormality” that somehow needs to be treated with a drug.



Author::::marya62
